        <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">How Dealer Finance Works</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">When you buy a car from a dealership, the dealer will almost always offer to arrange finance for you. This is called dealer finance or dealership finance. The dealer acts as an intermediary between you and a finance provider — they do not lend the money themselves. Instead, they have arrangements with one or more lenders and submit your application on your behalf.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Dealer finance is big business. For many dealerships, the finance and insurance (F&I) department is one of their most profitable areas. Dealers earn commission from the finance provider on every loan they arrange. This commission can be a flat fee, a percentage of the loan amount, or — critically — a margin above the lender's base rate. This last model is where dealer finance can become expensive for the consumer.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Here is how the rate margin model works: a lender might offer the dealer a base rate of 6.00% p.a. The dealer then has the discretion to add a margin — say 2% — making your rate 8.00% p.a. The dealer keeps the extra margin as commission. On a $35,000 loan over 5 years, that 2% margin costs you approximately $1,900 in additional interest. You would never know the base rate was lower because the dealer is not required to disclose the margin.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">This practice is legal in Australia. The National Consumer Credit Protection Act 2009 requires responsible lending but does not mandate that dealers offer you the lowest available rate. The dealer is required to ensure the finance is "not unsuitable" for you, but that is a much lower bar than "the best deal available".</p>
        </section>
