        <h2 class="font-montserrat font-bold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-[#1e3a5f] mb-6">Dealer Finance vs Broker: Detailed Comparison</h2>
        <h3 class="font-montserrat font-semibold text-xl text-[#0d4d3e] mt-8 mb-4">Interest Rates</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Dealer finance rates are often 1-4% higher than what you could arrange independently through a broker, due to the rate margin model. However, dealers sometimes offer manufacturer-subsidised promotional rates (often called "drive-away" or "1.9% finance" deals) that undercut broker rates on specific new models. These promotional rates are genuinely competitive when available, but they often come with restrictions — specific models only, maximum loan terms, no balloon payments, and sometimes mandatory dealer add-ons like paint protection or extended warranty.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Broker rates reflect the lender's actual rate for your credit profile. There is no hidden margin. The RBA reports the average fixed-term personal lending rate at 9.68% p.a. across the market. The best secured rate available through a broker is currently 4.99% p.a., and the average car loan rate for prime borrowers through broker channels is approximately 7.20% p.a.</p>
        <h3 class="font-montserrat font-semibold text-xl text-[#0d4d3e] mt-8 mb-4">Range of Options</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">A dealer typically works with 2-5 finance providers. A broker compares options from 130+ lenders. For borrowers with excellent credit, this difference may be minor — most lenders will offer a competitive rate. For borrowers with any complexity (self-employed, bad credit, unusual vehicle, large loan amount, specific structure like chattel mortgage), a broker's wider panel makes a significant difference because specialist lenders are often not available through dealers.</p>
        <h3 class="font-montserrat font-semibold text-xl text-[#0d4d3e] mt-8 mb-4">Speed and Convenience</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">This is where dealer finance has a genuine advantage. You can arrange finance on the spot, same day, while you are at the dealership. For some buyers, this convenience is valuable. Broker finance requires a separate application process — typically 24-48 hours for pre-approval, though initial assessments can be provided in minutes. If you plan ahead and get pre-approved before visiting the dealer, the speed advantage disappears.</p>
        <h3 class="font-montserrat font-semibold text-xl text-[#0d4d3e] mt-8 mb-4">Transparency</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Broker finance is generally more transparent. A broker shows you the rate, the comparison rate, all fees, and the total cost of the loan. Dealer finance can be less transparent — the focus is often on the monthly repayment rather than the total cost. A lower monthly repayment might disguise a longer term, a large balloon payment, or a higher interest rate. Always compare the total amount repayable, not just the monthly figure.</p>
        <h3 class="font-montserrat font-semibold text-xl text-[#0d4d3e] mt-8 mb-4">Pressure and Objectivity</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 font-lato font-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Dealer finance is arranged in a high-pressure sales environment. The dealer has already invested time in the vehicle sale and wants to close the deal, including the finance, today. This pressure can lead to suboptimal decisions. A broker consultation is separate, objective, and low-pressure. You can take your time, ask questions, and compare options without a salesperson waiting in the next room.</p>
        </section>
